Introduction¶

Dataset Source ¶

Singh, S. (2021). Loan Approval Prediction. Kaggle.com. Retrieved 6 April 2021, from https://www.kaggle.com/sonalisingh1411/loan-approval-prediction.

Dataset Details ¶

The Loan Approval Prediction dataset obtained from Kaggle.com contains the home loan applications from the Dream Housing Finance Company in the United States. The Dream Housing Finance Company offers financing for different kinds of home loans, across all urban, semi-urban and rural areas in the United States.

The dataset contains the details of applicants who has applied for a home loan through their online application form. These details include their Gender, Marital Status, Education Level, Number of Dependents, Income, Loan Amount, Loan Term, Credit History and others.

Dataset Features ¶

The dataset is a csv file which contains 11 features with 614 observations. The 11 variables are as follows:

Name of Feature Data Type Units Brief Description
Gender Categorical Not Applicable The gender of the applicant: Male / Female
Married Categorical Not Applicable The marriage status of the applicant: YES / NO
Dependents Categorical Person The number of dependent applicant has: 0 / 1 / 2 / 3+
Education Ordinal Categorical Not Applicable The applicant's education status: Graduate/ Under Graduate
SelfEmployed Categorical Not Applicable Self Employment status of applicant: YES / NO
ApplicantIncome Numerical USD Monthly Income of Applicant
CoapplicantIncome Numerical USD Monthly Income of Coapplicant
LoanAmount Numerical USD Loan Amount in Thousands
LoanAmountTerm Numerical Months Term of Loan
CreditHistory Binary Not Applicable Determine if Applicant's credit history has met with the guidelines : 1 (Met guidelines) / 0 (Did not meet guidelines)
PropertyArea Categorical Not Applicable Property Area of Applicants: Urban / Semi-Urban / Rural

Target Feature ¶

The targetted feature of the loan approval prediction dataset is as follows:

Name of Feature Data Type Units Brief Description
LoanStatus Categorical Not Applicable The approval status of the loan application: Y (Yes) / N (No)

Goals & Objectives ¶

The Dream Housing Finance company plans to automate and gain insights about an applicant's loan eligibility based on specific details provided by the applicant. They plan to segment customers who are eligible for their home loan from those who are not using automation.

Loan prediction is a common issue that each bank/loan company faces. They face the challenge of deciding whom they should extend credit to and on what basis that decision is made. Extending credit to an potentially default applicant will be costly. Not extending credit to an applicant would mean losing a potential customer.

Different supervised machine learning models will be fitted to the data, and each one will be evaluated on its accuracy and validity. A machine learning model would be built to help Dream Housing Finance classify if a loan application should be approved based on various variables such as Income, Loan Amount and Credit History.

Through this exercise we hope that our model will help banks/ loan companies understand how to better position themselves to understand and offer loans to applicants through the use of data and machine learning.

Removing ID-Like Columns ¶

The Loan_ID column would not be relevant in predictive modelling. By setting it as an ID-like column, the Loan_ID data would not be completely lost, yet it will not be a column anymore.

Adding new column Total Income ¶

Some of the home loans have coapplicants, therefore, the combined household income should be considered instead.

After aggregating the total household income, the individual applicant and coapplicant income would not be necessary and is therefore removed from the dataset.

In [ ]:
total_income = loan_df["ApplicantIncome"] + loan_df["CoapplicantIncome"]
loan_df.insert(5, "TotalHouseholdIncome", total_income, True)
#loan_df.drop(columns=["ApplicantIncome", "CoapplicantIncome"])
del loan_df["ApplicantIncome"]
del loan_df["CoapplicantIncome"]

Among those who met the credit history guidelines, 325 (79.3%) applicants had their loan granted approval and only 85 (20.7%) of them were not granted the loan approval.

Among those who did not meet the credit history guidelines only 7 (10%) of them were granted loan approval while 63 (90%) applicants were not.

Comparing the blue colored columns, if an applicant fulfills the credit history guidelines, the likelihood of the approval of their application would be higher.

Summary & Conclusions ¶

The Dream Housing Finance company is looking to automate and gain insights on their applicant's loan eligibility based on specific details provided by the applicants.

This project ultimately aims to build different supervised machine learning models to help Dream Housing Finance classify the loan status of their applicants. Each model will be evaluated on its accuracy and validity.

At phase 1 of the project, the loan approval data set is examined and pre-processed. This include ensuring that each features are of the right type, removing the ID-Like column, checking for missing values and checking the unique values for all categorical features.

A new column Total Household Income is added in the dataset by aggregating both "Applicant Income" and "Coapplicant Income" as the total income of the applicants are usually taken into consideration since they would most likely co-pay the home loans. As such, both Applicant Income and Coapplicant Income are removed from the dataset.

In addition, visualisations have been used to examine on how various variables might affect the loan status.

Through the visualisations, it is deduced that majority of the home loans are usually approved, with most applicants being male, graduates and have a good credit history. A positive credit history greatly affects the outcome of the loan status while being a graduate only has a small impact on the loan status. It is found that majority of the applicants have a total monthly household income of less than 10,000 USD and are requesting for loans amounting from 50k to 250k with a loan term of 360 days.

In addition, the gender of the applicants do not contribute much to the outcome of the loan status although it is found that the male applicants tend to generally have a higher income. The female applicants who have their loans approved have a higher average household income as compared to the females who do not have their loan approved.

Looking at property of the applicants, the applicants from the Semi-Urbanised Area are most likely to be granted loans, followed by the Urbanised Area and then the Rural Area. The average loan amount requested by the applicant staying in Rural Areas are the highest. Overall, across all property areas, loans that are approved have a lower average loan amount.

The data visualisation and exploration stage has given insight into what features may potentially be significant to the predication of their loan application status. This will aid in the selection of features in the future steps for creating the different machine learning models. The next phase for this project will involve exploring different machine learning algorithms with this processed dataset, and evaluating the accuracy and validity of each.
